SIMPLE: spy
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spy
<hw>Spy</hw> <pr>(sp⟦imac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Spied</conjf> <pr>(sp⟦imac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Spying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>spien</ets>,
<ets>espien</ets>, OF. <ets>espier</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧pier</ets>,
OHG. <ets>speh⟦omac⟧n</ets>, G. <ets>sp⟦aum⟧hen</ets>; akin to L.
<ets>specere</ets> to see, Skr. <ets>spa⟦cced⟧</ets>. ⟦root⟧ 169. Cf.
<er>Espy</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Aspect</er>, <er>Auspice</er>,
<er>Circumspect</er>, <er>Conspicuous</er>, <er>Despise</er>,
<er>Frontispiece</er>, <er>Inspect</er>, <er>Prospect</er>,
<er>Respite</er>, <er>Scope</er>, <er>Specimen</er>, <er>Spectacle</er>,
<er>Specter</er>, <er>Speculate</er>, <er>Spice</er>, <er>Spite</er>,
<er>Suspicion</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To gain sight of; to
discover at a distance, or in a state of concealment; to espy; to
see.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One, in reading, skipped over all sentences where he
<qex>spied</qex> a note of admiration.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To discover by close search or
examination.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Look about with your eyes; <qex>spy</qex> what things are to be
reformed in the church of England.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To explore; to view, inspect, and examine secretly,
as a country; -- usually with <ptcl>out</ptcl>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Moses sent to <qex>spy</qex> out Jaazer, and they took the
villages thereof.</q> <rj><qau>Num. xxi. 32.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spy
<hw>Spy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To search narrowly; to
scrutinize.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is my nature's plague⟦br⟧
To <qex>spy</qex> into abuses.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spy
<hw>Spy</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Spies</plw>
<pr>(sp⟦imac⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[See <er>Spy</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, and
cf. <er>Espy</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who keeps a
constant watch of the conduct of others.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧These wretched
<xex>spies</xex> of wit.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A person sent secretly into an
enemy's camp, territory, or fortifications, to inspect his works,
ascertain his strength, movements, or designs, and to communicate such
intelligence to the proper officer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spy money</b></col>, <cd>money paid to a spy; the reward
for private or secret intelligence regarding the enemy.</cd> --
<col><b>Spy Wednesday</b></col> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld>, <cd>the Wednesday
immediately preceding the festival of Easter; -- so called in allusion
to the betrayal of Christ by Judas Iscariot.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Emissary</er>, and
<er>Scout</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spyboat</ent>⟦br⟧
